f(x)=x(1-e^{-1/x}), \quad x>0
y=-\frac1x
(0,e^0)
(y,e^y)
 f(x) = \frac{e^y-1}{y}
f(x)
x>0
f\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)
\mathrm{e}^x > 1+x
x>0
    \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left( \frac{1-\exp(-x)}{x} \right) = \mathrm{e}^{-x} \frac{1+x-\mathrm{e}^{x}}{x} < 0 
x<0
x>y
-x,-y
-1/x>-1/y
\exp(-1/x)>\exp(-1/y)
1-\exp(-1/x)<1-\exp(-1/y)
x<0
x>y\to f(x)>f(y)
-x(1-e^{-1/x})<-x(1-e^{-1/y})<-y(1-e^{-1/y})
